No -- ComfyUI is not essentially a wrapper around Diffusers.

Better model:

Diffusers = Hugging Face pipeline framework
ComfyUI = graph/runtime + custom PyTorch model loaders/samplers/nodes

Comfy uses PyTorch tensors for core compute, but it has its own execution graph, model management, node system, loaders, caching/offloading behavior, and many custom nodes. Comfy’s docs say the core number crunching is PyTorch, not "Diffusers underneath."  ￼

For Wan2.2 specifically, the official repo lists separate integrations: inference code, ComfyUI integration, and Diffusers integration. That strongly implies Comfy is not just calling Diffusers; they are different paths into the same model family.  ￼

Your memory issue is plausible. Official Wan2.2 docs say A14B T2V/I2V single-GPU wants 80GB VRAM, while TI2V-5B can run on 24GB VRAM only with --offload_model True, --convert_model_dtype, and --t5_cpu.  ￼ Comfy also had Wan2.2-specific memory optimizations after release, including less VAE decode VRAM and major 5B I2V improvements.  ￼

So the difference may be:

Your raw Diffusers/PyTorch attempt:
loads too much at once
keeps text encoder / transformer / VAE resident
uses wrong dtype
does not offload aggressively
decodes video too eagerly
keeps tensors alive accidentally
Comfy:
custom loader
custom sampler nodes
model/vae/text encoder offload
GGUF/blockswap/custom quant nodes maybe
workflow-specific memory tricks

Also: people have reported Wan2.2 I2V using over 100GB combined RAM/swap/VRAM in Comfy workflows too, so it is not just you.  ￼

My advice: do not reimplement Wan22 inference yet. Make Beast call Comfy or official Wan scripts as the backend first.

Beast backend hierarchy:

BeastEngine
  ComfyBackend       <- first practical target
  WanOfficialBackend <- second
  DiffusersBackend   <- later
  NativeBackend      <- much later

For Beast2, Comfy is not "beneath you." It is a proven inference adapter. Let Beast own artifacts, CDI, gallery, reproducibility, generator UX. Let Comfy eat the Wan dragon for now.














